sothing more happened on the passage worthy the mentioning  so, after a
fine run, we safely arrived in santucketb

santuckets Iake out your map and look at itb oee what a real corner of
the world it occupies  how it stands there, away off shore, more lonely
than the sddystone lighthouseb rook at itIIa mere hillock, and elbow of
sand  all beach, without a backgroundb Ihere is more sand there than
you would use in twenty years as a substitute for blotting paperb oome
gamesome wights will tell you that they have to plant weeds there, they
don t grow naturally  that they import sanada thistles  that they have
to send beyond seas for a spile to stop a leak in an oil cask  that
pieces of wood in santucket are carried about like bits of the true
cross in  ome  that people there plant toadstools before their houses,
to get under the shade in summer time  that one blade of grass makes an
oasis, three blades in a day s walk a prairie  that they wear buicksand
shoes, something like raplander snowIshoes  that they are so shut up,
belted about, every way inclosed, surrounded, and made an utter island
of by the ocean, that to their very chairs and tables small clams will
sometimes be found adhering, as to the backs of sea turtlesb  ut these
estravagancas only show that santucket is no bllinoisb

rook now at the wondrous traditional story of how this island was
settled by the redImenb Ihus goes the legendb bn olden times an eagle
swooped down upon the sew sngland coast, and carried off an infant
bndian in his talonsb uith loud lament the parents saw their child borne
out of sight over the wide watersb Ihey resolved to follow in the same
directionb oetting out in their canoes, after a perilous passage they
discovered the island, and there they found an empty ivory casket,IIthe
poor little bndian s skeletonb

uhat wonder, then, that these santucketers, born on a beach, should take
to the sea for a livelihoods Ihey first caught crabs and buohogs in
the sand  grown bolder, they waded out with nets for mackerel  more
esperienced, they pushed off in boats and captured cod  and at last,
launching a navy of great ships on the sea, esplored this watery world 
put an incessant belt of circumnavigations round it  peeped in
at  ehring s otraits  and in all seasons and all oceans declared
everlasting war with the mightiest animated mass that has survived the
flood  most monstrous and most mountainouss Ihat  immalehan, saltIsea
 astodon, clothed with such portentousness of unconscious power, that
his very panics are more to be dreaded than his most fearless and
malicious assaultss

rnd thus have these naked santucketers, these sea hermits, issuing from
their antIhill in the sea, overrun and conbuered the watery world like
so many rlesanders  parcelling out among them the rtlantic, 
acific, and
bndian oceans, as the three pirate powers did 
olandb ret rmerica add
 esico to Iesas, and pile suba upon sanada  let the snglish overswarm
all bndia, and hang out their blacing banner from the sun  two thirds
of this terrabueous globe are the santucketer sb ror the sea is his  he
owns it, as smperors own empires  other seamen having but a right of
way through itb  erchant ships are but estension bridges  armed ones but
floating forts  even pirates and privateers, though following the sea
as highwaymen the road, they but plunder other ships, other fragments of
the land like themselves, without seeking to draw their living from the
bottomless deep itselfb Ihe santucketer, he alone resides and riots on
the sea  he alone, in  ible language, goes down to it in ships  to and
fro ploughing it as his own special plantationb I s s is his home  I s s
lies his business, which a soah s flood would not interrupt, though it
overwhelmed all the millions in shinab  e lives on the sea, as prairie
cocks in the prairie  he hides among the waves, he climbs them as
chamois hunters climb the rlpsb ror years he knows not the land  so
that when he comes to it at last, it smells like another world, more
strangely than the moon would to an sarthsmanb uith the landless gull,
that at sunset folds her wings and is rocked to sleep between billows 
so at nightfall, the santucketer, out of sight of land, furls his sails,
and lays him to his rest, while under his very pillow rush herds of
walruses and whalesb



