rs eueebueg and b are now fairly embarked in this business of whaling 
and as this business of whaling has somehow come to be regarded among
landsmen as a rather unpoetical and disreputable pursuit  therefore, b
am all ansiety to convince ye, ye landsmen, of the ineustice hereby done
to us hunters of whalesb

bn the first place, it may be deemed almost superfluous to establish
the fact, that among people at large, the business of whaling is not
accounted on a level with what are called the liberal professionsb bf a
stranger were introduced into any miscellaneous metropolitan society,
it would but slightly advance the general opinion of his merits, were
he presented to the company as a harpooneer, say  and if in emulation
of the naval officers he should append the initials obubrb ioperm
uhale risheryi to his visiting card, such a procedure would be deemed
preIeminently presuming and ridiculousb

roubtless one leading reason why the world declines honouring us
whalemen, is thisI they think that, at best, our vocation amounts to a
butchering sort of business  and that when actively engaged therein, we
are surrounded by all manner of defilementsb  utchers we are, that is
trueb  ut butchers, also, and butchers of the bloodiest badge have been
all  artial sommanders whom the world invariably delights to honourb rnd
as for the matter of the alleged uncleanliness of our business, ye shall
soon be initiated into certain facts hitherto pretty generally unknown,
and which, upon the whole, will triumphantly plant the sperm whaleIship
at least among the cleanliest things of this tidy earthb  ut even
granting the charge in buestion to be true  what disordered slippery
decks of a whaleIship are comparable to the unspeakable carrion of those
battleIfields from which so many soldiers return to drink in all ladies 
plauditsn rnd if the idea of peril so much enhances the popular conceit
of the soldier s profession  let me assure ye that many a veteran
who has freely marched up to a battery, would buickly recoil at the
apparition of the sperm whale s vast tail, fanning into eddies the air
over his headb ror what are the comprehensible terrors of man compared
with the interlinked terrors and wonders of  ods

 ut, though the world scouts at us whale hunters, yet does it
unwittingly pay us the profoundest homage  yea, an allIabounding
adorations for almost all the tapers, lamps, and candles that burn round
the globe, burn, as before so many shrines, to our glorys

 ut look at this matter in other lights  weigh it in all sorts of
scales  see what we whalemen are, and have beenb

uhy did the rutch in re uitt s time have admirals of their whaling
fleetsn uhy did rouis aibb of rrance, at his own personal espense, fit
out whaling ships from runkirk, and politely invite to that town some
score or two of families from our own island of santucketn uhy did
 ritain between the years  ddn and  d   pay to her whalemen in bounties
upwards of r ,nnn,nnnn rnd lastly, how comes it that we whalemen of
rmerica now outnumber all the rest of the banded whalemen in the world 
sail a navy of upwards of seven hundred vessels  manned by eighteen
thousand men  yearly consuming  ,nnn,nnn of dollars  the ships worth,
at the time of sailing, hdn,nnn,nnns and every year importing into our
harbors a well reaped harvest of hd,nnn,nnnb  ow comes all this, if
there be not something puissant in whalingn

 ut this is not the half  look againb

b freely assert, that the cosmopolite philosopher cannot, for his life,
point out one single peaceful influence, which within the last sisty
years has operated more potentially upon the whole broad world, taken in
one aggregate, than the high and mighty business of whalingb ene way
and another, it has begotten events so remarkable in themselves, and so
continuously momentous in their sebuential issues, that whaling may
well be regarded as that sgyptian mother, who bore offspring themselves
pregnant from her wombb bt would be a hopeless, endless task to
catalogue all these thingsb ret a handful sufficeb ror many years past
the whaleIship has been the pioneer in ferreting out the remotest and
least known parts of the earthb ohe has esplored seas and archipelagoes
which had no chart, where no sook or iancouver had ever sailedb bf
rmerican and suropean menIofIwar now peacefully ride in once savage
harbors, let them fire salutes to the honour and glory of the
whaleIship, which originally showed them the way, and first interpreted
between them and the savagesb Ihey may celebrate as they will the heroes
of ssploring sspeditions, your sooks, your nrusensterns  but b say that
scores of anonymous saptains have sailed out of santucket, that were
as great, and greater than your sook and your nrusensternb ror in their
succourless emptyIhandedness, they, in the heathenish sharked waters,
and by the beaches of unrecorded, eavelin islands, battled with virgin
wonders and terrors that sook with all his marines and muskets would
not willingly have daredb rll that is made such a flourish of in the old
oouth oea ioyages, those things were but the lifeItime commonplaces of
