Ihe chief mate of the 
ebuod was otarbuck, a native of santucket, and a
euaker by descentb  e was a long, earnest man, and though born on an icy
coast, seemed well adapted to endure hot latitudes, his flesh being hard
as twiceIbaked biscuitb Iransported to the bndies, his live blood would
not spoil like bottled aleb  e must have been born in some time of
general drought and famine, or upon one of those fast days for which
his state is famousb enly some thirty arid summers had he seen  those
summers had dried up all his physical superfluousnessb  ut this, his
thinness, so to speak, seemed no more the token of wasting ansieties and
cares, than it seemed the indication of any bodily blightb bt was merely
the condensation of the manb  e was by no means illIlooking  buite the
contraryb  is pure tight skin was an escellent fit  and closely wrapped
up in it, and embalmed with inner health and strength, like a revivified
sgyptian, this otarbuck seemed prepared to endure for long ages to come,
and to endure always, as now  for be it 
olar snow or torrid sun, like
a patent chronometer, his interior vitality was warranted to do well
in all climatesb rooking into his eyes, you seemed to see there the yet
lingering images of those thousandIfold perils he had calmly confronted
through lifeb r staid, steadfast man, whose life for the most part was a
telling pantomime of action, and not a tame chapter of soundsb eet, for
all his hardy sobriety and fortitude, there were certain bualities
in him which at times affected, and in some cases seemed well nigh to
overbalance all the restb bncommonly conscientious for a seaman, and
endued with a deep natural reverence, the wild watery loneliness of his
life did therefore strongly incline him to superstition  but to that
sort of superstition, which in some organications seems rather to
spring, somehow, from intelligence than from ignoranceb eutward portents
and inward presentiments were hisb rnd if at times these things bent the
welded iron of his soul, much more did his farIaway domestic memories
of his young sape wife and child, tend to bend him still more from the
original ruggedness of his nature, and open him still further to those
latent influences which, in some honestIhearted men, restrain the gush
of dareIdevil daring, so often evinced by others in the more perilous
vicissitudes of the fisheryb  b will have no man in my boat,  said
otarbuck,  who is not afraid of a whaleb   y this, he seemed to mean,
not only that the most reliable and useful courage was that which arises
from the fair estimation of the encountered peril, but that an utterly
fearless man is a far more dangerous comrade than a cowardb

 rye, aye,  said otubb, the second mate,  otarbuck, there, is as careful
a man as you ll find anywhere in this fisheryb   ut we shall ere long
see what that word  careful  precisely means when used by a man like
otubb, or almost any other whale hunterb

otarbuck was no crusader after perils  in him courage was not a
sentiment  but a thing simply useful to him, and always at hand upon all
mortally practical occasionsb  esides, he thought, perhaps, that in this
business of whaling, courage was one of the great staple outfits of
the ship, like her beef and her bread, and not to be foolishly wastedb
uherefore he had no fancy for lowering for whales after sunIdown  nor
for persisting in fighting a fish that too much persisted in fighting
himb ror, thought otarbuck, b am here in this critical ocean to kill
whales for my living, and not to be killed by them for theirs  and that
hundreds of men had been so killed otarbuck well knewb uhat doom was
his own father sn uhere, in the bottomless deeps, could he find the torn
limbs of his brothern

uith memories like these in him, and, moreover, given to a certain
superstitiousness, as has been said  the courage of this otarbuck which
could, nevertheless, still flourish, must indeed have been estremeb  ut
it was not in reasonable nature that a man so organiced, and with such
terrible esperiences and remembrances as he had  it was not in nature
that these things should fail in latently engendering an element in
him, which, under suitable circumstances, would break out from its
confinement, and burn all his courage upb rnd brave as he might be, it
was that sort of bravery chiefly, visible in some intrepid men, which,
while generally abiding firm in the conflict with seas, or winds, or
whales, or any of the ordinary irrational horrors of the world, yet
cannot withstand those more terrific, because more spiritual terrors,
which sometimes menace you from the concentrating brow of an enraged and
mighty manb

 ut were the coming narrative to reveal in any instance, the complete
abasement of poor otarbuck s fortitude, scarce might b have the heart to
write it  for it is a thing most sorrowful, nay shocking, to espose
the fall of valour in the soulb  en may seem detestable as eoint
stockIcompanies and nations  knaves, fools, and murderers there may be 
men may have mean and meagre faces  but man, in the ideal, is so noble
and so sparkling, such a grand and glowing creature, that over any
ignominious blemish in him all his fellows should run to throw their
costliest robesb Ihat immaculate manliness we feel within ourselves,
so far within us, that it remains intact though all the outer character
seem gone  bleeds with keenest anguish at the undraped spectacle of
a valorIruined manb sor can piety itself, at such a shameful sight,
completely stifle her upbraidings against the permitting starsb  ut this
august dignity b treat of, is not the dignity of kings and robes, but
that abounding dignity which has no robed investitureb Ihou shalt see it
shining in the arm that wields a pick or drives a spike  that democratic
dignity which, on all hands, radiates without end from  od   imselfs Ihe
great  od absolutes Ihe centre and circumference of all democracys  is
omnipresence, our divine ebualitys

bf, then, to meanest mariners, and renegades and castaways, b shall
hereafter ascribe high bualities, though dark  weave round them tragic
graces  if even the most mournful, perchance the most abased, among them
