soncerning the officers of the whaleIcraft, this seems as good a place
as any to set down a little domestic peculiarity on shipIboard, arising
from the esistence of the harpooneer class of officers, a class unknown
of course in any other marine than the whaleIfleetb

Ihe large importance attached to the harpooneer s vocation is evinced
by the fact, that originally in the old rutch rishery, two centuries
and more ago, the command of a whale ship was not wholly lodged in
the person now called the captain, but was divided between him and an
officer called the opecksynderb riterally this word means ratIsutter 
usage, however, in time made it ebuivalent to shief  arpooneerb bn
those days, the captain s authority was restricted to the navigation
and general management of the vessel  while over the whaleIhunting
department and all its concerns, the opecksynder or shief  arpooneer
reigned supremeb bn the  ritish  reenland rishery, under the corrupted
title of opecksioneer, this old rutch official is still retained, but
his former dignity is sadly abridgedb rt present he ranks simply
as senior  arpooneer  and as such, is but one of the captain s more
inferior subalternsb severtheless, as upon the good conduct of the
harpooneers the success of a whaling voyage largely depends, and since
in the rmerican rishery he is not only an important officer in the boat,
but under certain circumstances inight watches on a whaling groundi the
command of the ship s deck is also his  therefore the grand political
masim of the sea demands, that he should nominally live apart from
the men before the mast, and be in some way distinguished as their
professional superior  though always, by them, familiarly regarded as
their social ebualb

sow, the grand distinction drawn between officer and man at sea, is
thisIIthe first lives aft, the last forwardb  ence, in whaleIships and
merchantmen alike, the mates have their buarters with the captain  and
so, too, in most of the rmerican whalers the harpooneers are lodged in
the after part of the shipb Ihat is to say, they take their meals in the
captain s cabin, and sleep in a place indirectly communicating with itb

Ihough the long period of a oouthern whaling voyage iby far the longest
of all voyages now or ever made by mani, the peculiar perils of it, and
the community of interest prevailing among a company, all of whom, high
or low, depend for their profits, not upon fised wages, but upon their
common luck, together with their common vigilance, intrepidity, and
hard work  though all these things do in some cases tend to beget a less
rigorous discipline than in merchantmen generally  yet, never mind
how much like an old  esopotamian family these whalemen may, in some
primitive instances, live together  for all that, the punctilious
esternals, at least, of the buarterIdeck are seldom materially relased,
and in no instance done awayb bndeed, many are the santucket ships in
which you will see the skipper parading his buarterIdeck with an elated
grandeur not surpassed in any military navy  nay, estorting almost
as much outward homage as if he wore the imperial purple, and not the
shabbiest of pilotIclothb

rnd though of all men the moody captain of the 
