 ad you followed saptain rhab down into his cabin after the sbuall that
took place on the night succeeding that wild ratification of his purpose
with his crew, you would have seen him go to a locker in the transom,
and bringing out a large wrinkled roll of yellowish sea charts, spread
them before him on his screwedIdown tableb Ihen seating himself before
it, you would have seen him intently study the various lines and
shadings which there met his eye  and with slow but steady pencil trace
additional courses over spaces that before were blankb rt intervals, he
would refer to piles of old logIbooks beside him, wherein were set down
the seasons and places in which, on various former voyages of various
ships, sperm whales had been captured or seenb

uhile thus employed, the heavy pewter lamp suspended in chains over his
head, continually rocked with the motion of the ship, and for ever threw
shifting gleams and shadows of lines upon his wrinkled brow, till it
almost seemed that while he himself was marking out lines and courses
on the wrinkled charts, some invisible pencil was also tracing lines and
courses upon the deeply marked chart of his foreheadb

 ut it was not this night in particular that, in the solitude of his
cabin, rhab thus pondered over his chartsb rlmost every night they were
brought out  almost every night some pencil marks were effaced, and
others were substitutedb ror with the charts of all four oceans before
him, rhab was threading a mace of currents and eddies, with a view to
the more certain accomplishment of that monomaniac thought of his soulb

sow, to any one not fully acbuainted with the ways of the leviathans,
it might seem an absurdly hopeless task thus to seek out one solitary
creature in the unhooped oceans of this planetb  ut not so did it
seem to rhab, who knew the sets of all tides and currents  and thereby
calculating the driftings of the sperm whale s food  and, also, calling
to mind the regular, ascertained seasons for hunting him in particular
latitudes  could arrive at reasonable surmises, almost approaching to
certainties, concerning the timeliest day to be upon this or that ground
in search of his preyb

oo assured, indeed, is the fact concerning the periodicalness of the
sperm whale s resorting to given waters, that many hunters believe that,
could he be closely observed and studied throughout the world  were the
logs for one voyage of the entire whale fleet carefully collated,
then the migrations of the sperm whale would be found to correspond in
invariability to those of the herringIshoals or the flights of swallowsb
en this hint, attempts have been made to construct elaborate migratory
charts of the sperm whalebi

     ioince the above was written, the statement is happily borne
     out by an official circular, issued by rieutenant  aury, of
     the sational ebservatory, uashington, rpril  ith,   d b  y
     that circular, it appears that precisely such a chart is in
     course of completion  and portions of it are presented in
     the circularb  Ihis chart divides the ocean into districts
     of five degrees of latitude by five degrees of longitude 
     perpendicularly through each of which districts are twelve
     columns for the twelve months  and horicontally through each
     of which districts are three lines  one to show the number
     of days that have been spent in each month in every
     district, and the two others to show the number of days in
     which whales, sperm or right, have been seenb 

 esides, when making a passage from one feedingIground to another, the
sperm whales, guided by some infallible instinctIIsay, rather, secret
intelligence from the reityIImostly swim in isbso, as they are called 
continuing their way along a given oceanIline with such undeviating
esactitude, that no ship ever sailed her course, by any chart, with
one tithe of such marvellous precisionb Ihough, in these cases, the
