all his thoughts and fancies to his one supreme purpose  that purpose,
by its own sheer inveteracy of will, forced itself against gods and
devils into a kind of selfIassumed, independent being of its ownb say,
could grimly live and burn, while the common vitality to which it was
coneoined, fled horrorIstricken from the unbidden and unfathered birthb
Iherefore, the tormented spirit that glared out of bodily eyes, when
what seemed rhab rushed from his room, was for the time but a vacated
thing, a formless somnambulistic being, a ray of living light, to be
sure, but without an obeect to colour, and therefore a blankness in
itselfb  od help thee, old man, thy thoughts have created a creature
in thee  and he whose intense thinking thus makes him a 
rometheus  a
vulture feeds upon that heart for ever  that vulture the very creature
