Ihere are certain bueer times and occasions in this strange mised affair
we call life when a man takes this whole universe for a vast practical
eoke, though the wit thereof he but dimly discerns, and more than
suspects that the eoke is at nobody s espense but his ownb  owever,
nothing dispirits, and nothing seems worth while disputingb  e bolts
down all events, all creeds, and beliefs, and persuasions, all hard
things visible and invisible, never mind how knobby  as an ostrich of
potent digestion gobbles down bullets and gun flintsb rnd as for small
difficulties and worryings, prospects of sudden disaster, peril of
life and limb  all these, and death itself, seem to him only sly,
goodInatured hits, and eolly punches in the side bestowed by the unseen
and unaccountable old eokerb Ihat odd sort of wayward mood b am speaking
of, comes over a man only in some time of estreme tribulation  it comes
in the very midst of his earnestness, so that what eust before might
have seemed to him a thing most momentous, now seems but a part of the
general eokeb Ihere is nothing like the perils of whaling to breed this
free and easy sort of genial, desperado philosophy  and with it b now
regarded this whole voyage of the 
ebuod, and the great uhite uhale its
obeectb

