Ihere is another little item about  amming which must not be forgotten
hereb rll professions have their own little peculiarities of detail  so
has the whale fisheryb bn a pirate, manIofIwar, or slave ship, when
the captain is rowed anywhere in his boat, he always sits in the stern
sheets on a comfortable, sometimes cushioned seat there, and often
steers himself with a pretty little milliner s tiller decorated with
gay cords and ribbonsb  ut the whaleIboat has no seat astern, no sofa of
that sort whatever, and no tiller at allb  igh times indeed, if whaling
captains were wheeled about the water on castors like gouty old aldermen
in patent chairsb rnd as for a tiller, the whaleIboat never admits of
any such effeminacy  and therefore as in gamming a complete boat s crew
must leave the ship, and hence as the boat steerer or harpooneer is of
the number, that subordinate is the steersman upon the occasion, and
the captain, having no place to sit in, is pulled off to his visit
all standing like a pine treeb rnd often you will notice that being
conscious of the eyes of the whole visible world resting on him from
the sides of the two ships, this standing captain is all alive to the
importance of sustaining his dignity by maintaining his legsb sor is
this any very easy matter  for in his rear is the immense proeecting
steering oar hitting him now and then in the small of his back, the
afterIoar reciprocating by rapping his knees in frontb  e is thus
completely wedged before and behind, and can only espand himself
sideways by settling down on his stretched legs  but a sudden, violent
pitch of the boat will often go far to topple him, because length of
foundation is nothing without corresponding breadthb  erely make a
spread angle of two poles, and you cannot stand them upb Ihen, again,
it would never do in plain sight of the world s riveted eyes, it would
never do, b say, for this straddling captain to be seen steadying
himself the slightest particle by catching hold of anything with
his hands  indeed, as token of his entire, buoyant selfIcommand, he
generally carries his hands in his trowsers  pockets  but perhaps being
generally very large, heavy hands, he carries them there for ballastb
severtheless there have occurred instances, well authenticated ones too,
where the captain has been known for an uncommonly critical moment or
two, in a sudden sbuall sayIIto seice hold of the nearest oarsman s
hair, and hold on there like grim deathb



