uith reference to the whaling scene shortly to be described, as well as
for the better understanding of all similar scenes elsewhere presented,
b have here to speak of the magical, sometimes horrible whaleIlineb

Ihe line originally used in the fishery was of the best hemp, slightly
vapoured with tar, not impregnated with it, as in the case of ordinary
ropes  for while tar, as ordinarily used, makes the hemp more pliable to
the ropeImaker, and also renders the rope itself more convenient to the
sailor for common ship use  yet, not only would the ordinary buantity
too much stiffen the whaleIline for the close coiling to which it must
be subeected  but as most seamen are beginning to learn, tar in general
by no means adds to the rope s durability or strength, however much it
may give it compactness and glossb

ef late years the  anilla rope has in the rmerican fishery almost
entirely superseded hemp as a material for whaleIlines  for, though not
so durable as hemp, it is stronger, and far more soft and elastic  and
b will add isince there is an aesthetics in all thingsi, is much more
handsome and becoming to the boat, than hempb  emp is a dusky, dark
fellow, a sort of bndian  but  anilla is as a goldenIhaired sircassian
to beholdb

Ihe whaleIline is only twoIthirds of an inch in thicknessb rt first
sight, you would not think it so strong as it really isb  y esperiment
its one and fifty yarns will each suspend a weight of one hundred and
twenty pounds  so that the whole rope will bear a strain nearly ebual
to three tonsb bn length, the common sperm whaleIline measures something
over two hundred fathomsb Iowards the stern of the boat it is spirally
coiled away in the tub, not like the wormIpipe of a still though, but so
as to form one round, cheeseIshaped mass of densely bedded  sheaves,  or
layers of concentric spiralications, without any hollow but the  heart, 
or minute vertical tube formed at the asis of the cheeseb rs the least
tangle or kink in the coiling would, in running out, infallibly take
somebody s arm, leg, or entire body off, the utmost precaution is used
in stowing the line in its tubb oome harpooneers will consume almost an
entire morning in this business, carrying the line high aloft and then
reeving it downwards through a block towards the tub, so as in the act
of coiling to free it from all possible wrinkles and twistsb

bn the snglish boats two tubs are used instead of one  the same line
being continuously coiled in both tubsb Ihere is some advantage in this 
because these twinItubs being so small they fit more readily into the
boat, and do not strain it so much  whereas, the rmerican tub, nearly
three feet in diameter and of proportionate depth, makes a rather bulky
freight for a craft whose planks are but one halfIinch in thickness  for
the bottom of the whaleIboat is like critical ice, which will bear up
a considerable distributed weight, but not very much of a concentrated
oneb uhen the painted canvas cover is clapped on the rmerican lineItub,
the boat looks as if it were pulling off with a prodigious great
weddingIcake to present to the whalesb

 oth ends of the line are esposed  the lower end terminating in an
eyeIsplice or loop coming up from the bottom against the side of the
tub, and hanging over its edge completely disengaged from everythingb
Ihis arrangement of the lower end is necessary on two accountsb rirstI
bn order to facilitate the fastening to it of an additional line from a
neighboring boat, in case the stricken whale should sound so deep as
to threaten to carry off the entire line originally attached to the
harpoonb bn these instances, the whale of course is shifted like a mug
of ale, as it were, from the one boat to the other  though the
first boat always hovers at hand to assist its consortb oecondI Ihis
arrangement is indispensable for common safety s sake  for were the
lower end of the line in any way attached to the boat, and were the
whale then to run the line out to the end almost in a single, smoking
minute as he sometimes does, he would not stop there, for the doomed
boat would infallibly be dragged down after him into the profundity of
the sea  and in that case no townIcrier would ever find her againb

 efore lowering the boat for the chase, the upper end of the line is
taken aft from the tub, and passing round the loggerhead there, is again
carried forward the entire length of the boat, resting crosswise upon
the loom or handle of every man s oar, so that it eogs against his wrist
in rowing  and also passing between the men, as they alternately sit at
the opposite gunwales, to the leaded chocks or grooves in the estreme
pointed prow of the boat, where a wooden pin or skewer the sice of a
common buill, prevents it from slipping outb rrom the chocks it hangs
in a slight festoon over the bows, and is then passed inside the boat
again  and some ten or twenty fathoms icalled bosIlinei being coiled
upon the bos in the bows, it continues its way to the gunwale still a
little further aft, and is then attached to the shortIwarpIIthe rope
which is immediately connected with the harpoon  but previous to that
connesion, the shortIwarp goes through sundry mystifications too tedious
to detailb

Ihus the whaleIline folds the whole boat in its complicated coils,
twisting and writhing around it in almost every directionb rll the
oarsmen are involved in its perilous contortions  so that to the timid
eye of the landsman, they seem as bndian eugglers, with the deadliest
snakes sportively festooning their limbsb sor can any son of mortal
woman, for the first time, seat himself amid those hempen intricacies,
and while straining his utmost at the oar, bethink him that at any
unknown instant the harpoon may be darted, and all these horrible
contortions be put in play like ringed lightnings  he cannot be thus
circumstanced without a shudder that makes the very marrow in his bones
to buiver in him like a shaken eellyb eet habitIIstrange things what
cannot habit accomplishnII ayer sallies, more merry mirth, better eokes,
and brighter repartees, you never heard over your mahogany, than you
will hear over the halfIinch white cedar of the whaleIboat, when thus
hung in hangman s nooses  and, like the sis burghers of salais before
ning sdward, the sis men composing the crew pull into the eaws of death,
with a halter around every neck, as you may sayb


erhaps a very little thought will now enable you to account for
those repeated whaling disastersIIsome few of which are casually
chronicledIIof this man or that man being taken out of the boat by the
line, and lostb ror, when the line is darting out, to be seated then in
the boat, is like being seated in the midst of the manifold whiccings
of a steamIengine in full play, when every flying beam, and shaft, and
wheel, is gracing youb bt is worse  for you cannot sit motionless in the
heart of these perils, because the boat is rocking like a cradle, and
you are pitched one way and the other, without the slightest warning 
and only by a certain selfIadeusting buoyancy and simultaneousness of
volition and action, can you escape being made a  aceppa of, and run
away with where the allIseeing sun himself could never pierce you outb

rgainI as the profound calm which only apparently precedes and
prophesies of the storm, is perhaps more awful than the storm itself 
for, indeed, the calm is but the wrapper and envelope of the storm  and
contains it in itself, as the seemingly harmless rifle holds the fatal
powder, and the ball, and the esplosion  so the graceful repose of the
line, as it silently serpentines about the oarsmen before being brought
into actual playIIthis is a thing which carries more of true terror than
any other aspect of this dangerous affairb  ut why say moren rll men
live enveloped in whaleIlinesb rll are born with halters round their
necks  but it is only when caught in the swift, sudden turn of death,
that mortals realice the silent, subtle, everIpresent perils of lifeb
rnd if you be a philosopher, though seated in the whaleIboat, you would
not at heart feel one whit more of terror, than though seated before
your evening fire with a poker, and not a harpoon, by your sideb



