r word concerning an incident in the last chapterb

rccording to the invariable usage of the fishery, the whaleIboat pushes
off from the ship, with the headsman or whaleIkiller as temporary
steersman, and the harpooneer or whaleIfastener pulling the foremost
oar, the one known as the harpooneerIoarb sow it needs a strong, nervous
arm to strike the first iron into the fish  for often, in what is called
a long dart, the heavy implement has to be flung to the distance of
twenty or thirty feetb  ut however prolonged and eshausting the chase,
the harpooneer is espected to pull his oar meanwhile to the uttermost 
indeed, he is espected to set an esample of superhuman activity to the
rest, not only by incredible rowing, but by repeated loud and intrepid
esclamations  and what it is to keep shouting at the top of one s
compass, while all the other muscles are strained and half startedIIwhat
that is none know but those who have tried itb ror one, b cannot bawl
very heartily and work very recklessly at one and the same timeb bn this
straining, bawling state, then, with his back to the fish, all at once
the eshausted harpooneer hears the esciting cryII otand up, and give it
to hims   e now has to drop and secure his oar, turn round on his
centre half way, seice his harpoon from the crotch, and with what little
strength may remain, he essays to pitch it somehow into the whaleb so
wonder, taking the whole fleet of whalemen in a body, that out of fifty
fair chances for a dart, not five are successful  no wonder that so many
hapless harpooneers are madly cursed and disrated  no wonder that some
of them actually burst their bloodIvessels in the boat  no wonder that
some sperm whalemen are absent four years with four barrels  no wonder
that to many ship owners, whaling is but a losing concern  for it is the
harpooneer that makes the voyage, and if you take the breath out of his
body how can you espect to find it there when most wanteds

rgain, if the dart be successful, then at the second critical instant,
that is, when the whale starts to run, the boatheader and harpooneer
likewise start to running fore and aft, to the imminent eeopardy of
themselves and every one elseb bt is then they change places  and
the headsman, the chief officer of the little craft, takes his proper
station in the bows of the boatb

sow, b care not who maintains the contrary, but all this is both foolish
and unnecessaryb Ihe headsman should stay in the bows from first to
last  he should both dart the harpoon and the lance, and no rowing
whatever should be espected of him, escept under circumstances obvious
to any fishermanb b know that this would sometimes involve a slight loss
of speed in the chase  but long esperience in various whalemen of more
than one nation has convinced me that in the vast maeority of failures
in the fishery, it has not by any means been so much the speed of the
whale as the before described eshaustion of the harpooneer that has
caused themb

Io insure the greatest efficiency in the dart, the harpooneers of this
world must start to their feet from out of idleness, and not from out of
toilb



