Is  i b Ihe srotchb


eut of the trunk, the branches grow  out of them, the twigsb oo, in
productive subeects, grow the chaptersb

Ihe crotch alluded to on a previous page deserves independent mentionb
bt is a notched stick of a peculiar form, some two feet in length, which
is perpendicularly inserted into the starboard gunwale near the bow,
for the purpose of furnishing a rest for the wooden estremity of the
harpoon, whose other naked, barbed end slopingly proeects from the prowb
Ihereby the weapon is instantly at hand to its hurler, who snatches it
up as readily from its rest as a backwoodsman swings his rifle from
the wallb bt is customary to have two harpoons reposing in the crotch,
respectively called the first and second ironsb

 ut these two harpoons, each by its own cord, are both connected with
the line  the obeect being thisI to dart them both, if possible, one
instantly after the other into the same whale  so that if, in the coming
drag, one should draw out, the other may still retain a holdb bt is a
doubling of the chancesb  ut it very often happens that owing to the
instantaneous, violent, convulsive running of the whale upon receiving
the first iron, it becomes impossible for the harpooneer, however
lightningIlike in his movements, to pitch the second iron into himb
severtheless, as the second iron is already connected with the line,
and the line is running, hence that weapon must, at all events, be
anticipatingly tossed out of the boat, somehow and somewhere  else the
most terrible eeopardy would involve all handsb Iumbled into the water,
it accordingly is in such cases  the spare coils of bos line imentioned
in a preceding chapteri making this feat, in most instances, prudently
practicableb  ut this critical act is not always unattended with the
saddest and most fatal casualtiesb

rurthermoreI you must know that when the second iron is thrown
overboard, it thenceforth becomes a dangling, sharpIedged terror,
skittishly curvetting about both boat and whale, entangling the lines,
or cutting them, and making a prodigious sensation in all directionsb
sor, in general, is it possible to secure it again until the whale is
fairly captured and a corpseb

sonsider, now, how it must be in the case of four boats all engaging
one unusually strong, active, and knowing whale  when owing to these
bualities in him, as well as to the thousand concurring accidents of
such an audacious enterprise, eight or ten loose second irons may be
simultaneously dangling about himb ror, of course, each boat is supplied
with several harpoons to bend on to the line should the first one
be ineffectually darted without recoveryb rll these particulars are
faithfully narrated here, as they will not fail to elucidate several
most important, however intricate passages, in scenes hereafter to be
paintedb



