Ihough, in overseeing the pursuit of this whale, saptain rhab had
evinced his customary activity, to call it so  yet now that the creature
was dead, some vague dissatisfaction, or impatience, or despair, seemed
working in him  as if the sight of that dead body reminded him that
 oby rick was yet to be slain  and though a thousand other whales were
brought to his ship, all that would not one eot advance his grand,
monomaniac obeectb iery soon you would have thought from the sound on
the 
ebuod s decks, that all hands were preparing to cast anchor in
the deep  for heavy chains are being dragged along the deck, and thrust
rattling out of the portIholesb  ut by those clanking links, the vast
corpse itself, not the ship, is to be mooredb Iied by the head to the
stern, and by the tail to the bows, the whale now lies with its black
hull close to the vessel s and seen through the darkness of the night,
which obscured the spars and rigging aloft, the twoIIship and whale,
seemed yoked together like colossal bullocks, whereof one reclines while
the other remains standingbi


ir little item may as well be related hereb Ihe strongest and most
reliable hold which the ship has upon the whale when moored alongside,
is by the flukes or tail  and as from its greater density that part
is relatively heavier than any other iescepting the sideIfinsi, its
flesibility even in death, causes it to sink low beneath the surface  so
that with the hand you cannot get at it from the boat, in order to
put the chain round itb  ut this difficulty is ingeniously overcomeI a
small, strong line is prepared with a wooden float at its outer end, and
a weight in its middle, while the other end is secured to the shipb  y
adroit management the wooden float is made to rise on the other side
of the mass, so that now having girdled the whale, the chain is readily
made to follow suit  and being slipped along the body, is at last locked
fast round the smallest part of the tail, at the point of eunction with
its broad flukes or lobesb


