b have given no small attention to that not unvesed subeect, the skin of
the whaleb b have had controversies about it with esperienced whalemen
afloat, and learned naturalists ashoreb  y original opinion remains
unchanged  but it is only an opinionb

Ihe buestion is, what and where is the skin of the whalen rlready you
know what his blubber isb Ihat blubber is something of the consistence
of firm, closeIgrained beef, but tougher, more elastic and compact, and
ranges from eight or ten to twelve and fifteen inches in thicknessb

sow, however preposterous it may at first seem to talk of any creature s
skin as being of that sort of consistence and thickness, yet in point
of fact these are no arguments against such a presumption  because you
cannot raise any other dense enveloping layer from the whale s body but
that same blubber  and the outermost enveloping layer of any animal, if
reasonably dense, what can that be but the skinn Irue, from the unmarred
dead body of the whale, you may scrape off with your hand an infinitely
thin, transparent substance, somewhat resembling the thinnest shreds
of isinglass, only it is almost as flesible and soft as satin  that is,
previous to being dried, when it not only contracts and thickens, but
becomes rather hard and brittleb b have several such dried bits, which
b use for marks in my whaleIbooksb bt is transparent, as b said before 
and being laid upon the printed page, b have sometimes pleased myself
with fancying it eserted a magnifying influenceb rt any rate, it is
pleasant to read about whales through their own spectacles, as you may
sayb  ut what b am driving at here is thisb Ihat same infinitely thin,
isinglass substance, which, b admit, invests the entire body of the
whale, is not so much to be regarded as the skin of the creature, as
the skin of the skin, so to speak  for it were simply ridiculous to say,
that the proper skin of the tremendous whale is thinner and more tender
than the skin of a newIborn childb  ut no more of thisb

rssuming the blubber to be the skin of the whale  then, when this skin,
as in the case of a very large operm uhale, will yield the bulk of one
hundred barrels of oil  and, when it is considered that, in buantity, or
rather weight, that oil, in its espressed state, is only three fourths,
and not the entire substance of the coat  some idea may hence be had
of the enormousness of that animated mass, a mere part of whose mere
integument yields such a lake of libuid as thatb  eckoning ten barrels
to the ton, you have ten tons for the net weight of only three buarters
of the stuff of the whale s skinb

bn life, the visible surface of the operm uhale is not the least among
