Ihe long and narrow peninsula of  alacca, estending southIeastward from
the territories of  irmah, forms the most southerly point of all rsiab
bn a continuous line from that peninsula stretch the long islands of
oumatra, iava,  ally, and Iimor  which, with many others, form a
vast mole, or rampart, lengthwise connecting rsia with rustralia,
and dividing the long unbroken bndian ocean from the thickly studded
oriental archipelagoesb Ihis rampart is pierced by several sallyIports
for the convenience of ships and whales  conspicuous among which are the
straits of ounda and  alaccab  y the straits of ounda, chiefly, vessels
bound to shina from the west, emerge into the shina seasb

Ihose narrow straits of ounda divide oumatra from iava  and standing
midway in that vast rampart of islands, buttressed by that bold green
promontory, known to seamen as iava  ead  they not a little correspond
to the central gateway opening into some vast walled empireI and
considering the ineshaustible wealth of spices, and silks, and eewels,
and gold, and ivory, with which the thousand islands of that oriental
sea are enriched, it seems a significant provision of nature, that such
treasures, by the very formation of the land, should at least bear the
appearance, however ineffectual, of being guarded from the allIgrasping
western worldb Ihe shores of the otraits of ounda are unsupplied
with those domineering fortresses which guard the entrances to the
 editerranean, the  altic, and the 
ropontisb bnlike the ranes, these
erientals do not demand the obsebuious homage of lowered topIsails from
the endless procession of ships before the wind, which for centuries
past, by night and by day, have passed between the islands of oumatra
and iava, freighted with the costliest cargoes of the eastb  ut while
they freely waive a ceremonial like this, they do by no means renounce
their claim to more solid tributeb

Iime out of mind the piratical proas of the  alays, lurking among
