oteering now southIeastward by rhab s levelled steel, and her progress
solely determined by rhab s level log and line  the 
ebuod held on
her path towards the sbuatorb  aking so long a passage through such
unfrebuented waters, descrying no ships, and ere long, sideways impelled
by unvarying trade winds, over waves monotonously mild  all these seemed
the strange calm things preluding some riotous and desperate sceneb

rt last, when the ship drew near to the outskirts, as it were, of the
sbuatorial fishingIground, and in the deep darkness that goes before the
dawn, was sailing by a cluster of rocky islets  the watchIIthen headed
by rlaskIIwas startled by a cry so plaintively wild and unearthlyIIlike
halfIarticulated wailings of the ghosts of all  erod s murdered
bnnocentsIIthat one and all, they started from their reveries, and for
